{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017TppgxeXyLmXXie4YUcFtD","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: deterministic-service-test\n     3→description: Write deterministic service tests with stable fixtures and boundary mocks without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Deterministic Service Test (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill when creating tests for service modules.\n     9→\n    10→## Required Variables\n    11→\n    12→- `service_symbol`\n    13→- `module_path`\n    14→- `create_method`\n    15→- `cancel_method`\n    16→\n    17→## Execution Checklist\n    18→\n    19→1. Use deterministic input values (time/data/randomness controlled).\n    20→2. Keep one behavior per test function.\n    21→3. Include a visible `# Act` section in each test.\n    22→4. Mock only external boundaries and use autospec-capable mocks.\n    23→5. Avoid test coupling through shared mutable state.\n    24→\n    25→## Guardrails\n    26→\n    27→- No `unittest.TestCase` in pytest-style tasks.\n    28→- No real clock/random dependencies in deterministic tests.\n    29→- Keep assertions behavior-focused and minimal.\n    30→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fdaac483-5bf5-46a4-a053-2f36124816d0","uuid":"87bbc29c-81f3-4442-89a8-5b086d863369"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01GfGMiUxshBcNZnwpr81hZi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The file is a benign skill checklist (markdown). Not malicious.\n\nSkill checklist for `CoreService` from `services.core_service` with `create_record` and `cancel_record`:\n\n1. **Deterministic inputs** — fix time/data/randomness (e.g., freeze clocks, pass explicit timestamps/IDs).\n2. **One behavior per test** — separate tests for `create_record` success, `cancel_record` success, and each failure mode.\n3. **Visible `# Act`** — each test has an explicit `# Arrange` / `# Act` / `# Assert` structure with `# Act` present.\n4. **Boundary mocks with autospec** — mock only external boundaries (DB, clock, external APIs) using `mock.create_autospec` or `autospec=True`.\n5. **No shared mutable state** — use fresh fixtures per test; avoid module-level state.\n\nGuardrails: pytest-style only (no `unittest.TestCase`), no real clock/random, minimal behavior-focused assertions."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":630,"cache_read_input_tokens":21626,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":630,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":338,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fdaac483-5bf5-46a4-a053-2f36124816d0","uuid":"cbc5cc86-df82-4541-80ac-7405872c8523"}
